🔑 Problem Restatement
You’re given a binary tree.

Each node has a treasure value.

You need to check if there exists a root‑to‑leaf path such that the sum of values along the path equals targetSum.

A leaf = node with no children.

Return true if such a path exists, otherwise false.

🧩 DSA Concept & Pattern
Concept: Tree traversal with cumulative sum.

Pattern: DFS recursion (Depth‑First Search).

Why DFS? Because you need to explore all root‑to‑leaf paths.

At each node, subtract its value from the target.

If you reach a leaf and the remaining target = 0 → success.

👉 Memory trick:
“Path Sum = DFS down the tree, subtracting target.”

✅ Approach
If the tree is empty → return false.

Start DFS from the root with targetSum.

At each node:

Subtract node->val from targetSum.

If it’s a leaf and targetSum == 0 → return true.

Otherwise, recurse left and right.

If any path returns true, the answer is true.

If none do, return false.

📌 C++ Code (Core Logic)
cpp
struct TreeNode {
    int val;
    TreeNode* left;
    TreeNode* right;
    TreeNode(int x) : val(x), left(NULL), right(NULL) {}
};

class Solution {
public:
    bool hasPathSum(TreeNode* root, int targetSum) {
        if (!root) return false;
        // If leaf node
        if (!root->left && !root->right) {
            return targetSum == root->val;
        }
        // Recurse left or right
        return hasPathSum(root->left, targetSum - root->val) ||
               hasPathSum(root->right, targetSum - root->val);
    }
};
